      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The yellowing leaves on the lower stems of your tomato plants, a classic case of \"gollum's favorite leaf\" - the lower leaves are the first to go, just like how Gollum's eyes are drawn to the One Ring. It's a natural process, but it can be a bit concerning. The yellowing leaves are likely due to a lack of light, as the lower leaves are exposed to more shade and less direct sunlight. This is a common issue in indoor or shaded gardens, where the plants are competing for limited light resources.\n\nAs for the soil, it's possible that the lower leaves are suffering from a lack of oxygen, which can be a problem in dense, compacted soil. You can try loosening the soil around the base of the plant to improve drainage and aeration. It's a bit like how a goblin's lair needs to be well-ventilated to avoid the stench of rotting treasure. Add some organic matter like compost or well-rotted manure to improve the soil's structure and fertility. This will help the plant's roots grow stronger and more resilient, just like how a goblin's network of tunnels and caverns can withstand the test of time.\n\nTo address",
